<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "Who traditionally pays for a wedding?", answer: "In the traditional Western model, the bride's family pays for most of the wedding (around 55%), the groom's family covers a smaller share (around 15%, including the rehearsal dinner and sometimes the honeymoon), and the couple themselves pay for the remainder (around 30%). The tradition dates to the dowry system, where the bride's family was expected to demonstrate their daughter's value through a generous wedding. Modern couples increasingly pay for their own weddings, which is why the modern split flips the ratios." },
  { question: "What is the modern wedding cost split?", answer: "The modern split has the couple paying about 50% of the total, with the bride's and groom's families splitting the remaining 50% evenly (25% each). This reflects the reality that most couples in their late 20s and 30s have established careers and prefer to fund their own weddings to avoid the strings that come with parental contributions. The Knot's annual surveys show this is now the most common arrangement in the US." },
  { question: "Should both families contribute equally?", answer: "Many modern couples choose an even three-way split (33% bride's family, 33% groom's family, 33% couple) as a fair middle ground that acknowledges both families equally and avoids any expectation about which family 'gives' the bride away. This approach works best when both families have roughly similar means and the couple wants to keep things uncomplicated. It can be awkward when one family has significantly more money than the other." },
  { question: "How do same-sex couples split wedding costs?", answer: "Same-sex couples typically use the modern or even split since the traditional model doesn't apply. Many couples ask each set of parents to contribute equally, then cover the rest themselves. Surveys from the Williams Institute and The Knot show same-sex weddings average slightly less than opposite-sex weddings in the US, partly because the per-person cost is similar but couples are more likely to have smaller, more intimate guest lists." },
  { question: "What if one family can't or won't contribute?", answer: "It happens often. If one family can't contribute, the couple covers the gap (usually shifting to a 60/20/20 or 70/15/15 split). If one family won't contribute, the couple needs to decide whether to scale back, fund the difference themselves, or push back politely. The most important thing is to have the money conversation early — before the budget is set — so no one is surprised when it's time to pay vendors." }
]) %>

